Project description =
The Chicago Weather App is a desktop application made using Java and JavaFX. It shows real-time weather data from the National 
Weather Service (NWS) API. The app has two main screens: one for today’s weather and one for a 3-day forecast. The first screen 
shows the temperature, weather condition, and chance of precipitation. The second screen shows the forecast for the next three days, 
including day and night temperatures and wind information. I built this project using Java for the main code and JavaFX to create
the user interface. I also used Maven to help run and manage the project. The weather data comes from an API, and I used the
provided code to get that data and display it in my app. I also used two design patterns (Adapter and Template Method) to organize
my code better and make it easier to understand. While working on this project, I focused on making the app easy to use and clear to 
understand. I added colors and labels so users know what they are looking at. For my above and beyond feature, I added precipitation 
probability so users can see the chance of rain. I also fixed small bugs like making sure the app runs with Maven and that switching
between screens works correctly. Overall, this project helped me learn how to build a Java application, use an API, and design a 
simple user interface.

